              <div class="value" id="rCoverage">0</div>
              <div class="desc">sq ft of tile</div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="cost-breakdown" id="costBreakdown">
            <div class="cost-row">
              <span class="cost-label">Tile area (with waste)</span>
              <span class="cost-val" id="cTileArea">0 sq ft</span>
            </div>
            <div class="cost-row">
              <span class="cost-label">Tile cost</span>
              <span class="cost-val" id="cTile">$0.00</span>
            </div>
            <div class="cost-row">
              <span class="cost-label">Grout estimate (~$0.50/sq ft)</span>
              <span class="cost-val" id="cGrout">$0.00</span>
            </div>
            <div class="cost-row">
              <span class="cost-label">Adhesive estimate (~$0.75/sq ft)</span>
              <span class="cost-val" id="cAdhesive">$0.00</span>
            </div>
            <div class="cost-row total">
              <span class="cost-label">Total Material Cost</span>
              <span class="cost-val" id="cTotal">$0.00</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Tips -->
      <div class="card">
        <h2>Tile Installation Tips</h2>
        <div class="tip-item"><strong>1. Always buy extra</strong><p>Even with a waste factor built in, keep a few spare tiles for future repairs. Tile dye lots vary, so matching later may be impossible.</p></div>
        <div class="tip-item"><strong>2. Dry-lay before installing</strong><p>Place tiles on the floor without adhesive to check the layout, centering, and cut sizes before committing.</p></div>
        <div class="tip-item"><strong>3. Use spacers consistently</strong><p>Tile spacers ensure uniform grout lines. Match your spacer size to the grout width you selected — uneven lines are the most visible DIY mistake.</p></div>
        <div class="tip-item"><strong>4. Start from the center</strong><p>Find the center of the room and snap chalk lines. Starting from the center ensures symmetrical cuts along all walls.</p></div>
        <div class="tip-item"><strong>5. Account for obstacles</strong><p>Toilets, vanities, islands, and door frames reduce total area but increase cuts. Add 5% extra for rooms with many obstacles.</p></div>
        <div class="tip-item"><strong>6. Choose the right adhesive</strong><p>Use thin-set mortar for floor tiles and mastic for wall tiles in dry areas. Large-format tiles (over 15") need medium-bed mortar.</p></div>
      </div>

      <!-- SEO / FAQ Content -->
      <div class="seo-content">
        <h2>How to Calculate Tile Square Footage</h2>
        <p>Calculating how much tile you need is straightforward. Measure the room length and width, multiply them to get the total area, then divide by the area of each tile. The formula:</p>
        <div class="formula-box">Tiles Needed = (Room Area ÷ Tile Area) × (1 + Waste Factor)</div>
        <p>For example, a 10 × 12 foot room is 120 sq ft. Using 12×12 inch tiles (1 sq ft each), you need 120 tiles — plus 10% waste = <strong>132 tiles</strong>. If tiles come 10 per box, you need <strong>14 boxes</strong>.</p>

        <h2>Understanding Tile Sizes</h2>
        <p>Tile sizes are measured in inches (width × height). The most common floor tile sizes are 12×12, 12×24, 18×18, and 24×24 inches. Smaller tiles like 6×6 and 4×4 inches are popular for backsplashes and accent walls. Larger tiles create fewer grout lines for a cleaner, modern look but require a flatter subfloor and more precise installation.</p>

        <h2>Tile Patterns and Waste</h2>
        <p>Your tile layout pattern directly affects how much waste you'll have:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Straight lay (grid):</strong> The simplest pattern with tiles aligned in rows and columns. Produces the least waste (~10%) and is the easiest to install.</li>
          <li><strong>Diagonal (45°):</strong> Tiles are rotated 45 degrees. Creates a dynamic look but requires angled cuts along every wall edge, increasing waste to ~15%.</li>
          <li><strong>Herringbone:</strong> Rectangular tiles arranged in a V-shape. Visually striking but the most complex to install, with ~20% waste due to many angled cuts.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>How Grout Width Affects Your Project</h2>
        <p>Grout lines serve both functional and aesthetic purposes. Narrower grout lines (1/16" to 1/8") give a sleek, modern look but require rectified (precisely cut) tiles. Wider lines (1/4" to 1/2") are more forgiving of tile size variations and are recommended for natural stone. Grout width affects the effective tile size, which slightly changes how many tiles you need.</p>

        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <h3>How do I calculate how much tile I need?</h3>
        <p>Multiply your room's length by its width to get total square footage. Divide that by the area of one tile (in square feet). Add 10% for straight lay, 15% for diagonal, or 20% for herringbone patterns to cover cuts and waste.</p>

        <h3>How much extra tile should I buy for waste?</h3>
        <p>For standard straight lay, add 10%. Diagonal patterns need about 15% extra, and herringbone needs 20%. If the room has many obstacles (columns, curves, alcoves), add an additional 5%.</p>

        <h3>Does grout width affect how many tiles I need?</h3>
        <p>Yes. Wider grout lines mean each tile-plus-grout unit covers more area, slightly reducing the number of tiles needed. The difference is small for typical grout widths but can be noticeable on large projects with wide grout joints.</p>

        <h3>What is the most popular tile size for floors?</h3>
        <p>12×12 inch and 12×24 inch tiles are the most popular for floors. Larger formats like 24×24 are trending for modern spaces. Smaller tiles (6×6, mosaic) are best for backsplashes and shower floors.</p>

        <h3>How much does it cost to tile a room?</h3>
        <p>Materials typically cost $2–$15/sq ft depending on tile type. Add $0.50–$1.50/sq ft for grout and adhesive. Professional installation adds $5–$15/sq ft. A 120 sq ft room with mid-range tile ($5/sq ft) costs roughly $750–$900 in materials.</p>

        <h3>What tile pattern wastes the least material?</h3>
        <p>Straight lay (grid pattern) wastes the least — about 10%. Diagonal wastes ~15% and herringbone ~20%. Straight lay is also the fastest and easiest pattern to install.</p>

        <h3>How many tiles come in a box?</h3>
        <p>It varies by size. 12×12" tiles usually come 10–15 per box. 6×6" tiles may have 40–50 per box. Large 24×24" tiles come 4–6 per box. Check the box label for exact tile count and total coverage in square feet.</p>

        <h2>Related Calculators</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="/solar-panel-calculator" style="color:var(--accent-color);">Solar Panel Calculator</a> — Estimate savings from going solar based on your location and roof size</li>
          <li><a href="/electricity-cost-calculator" style="color:var(--accent-color);">Electricity Cost Calculator</a> — Calculate the cost to run any appliance or your whole household</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </main>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    var TILE_SIZES = [
      ["6×6", 6, 6],
      ["6×24", 6, 24],
      ["12×12", 12, 12],
      ["18×18", 18, 18],
      ["24×24", 24, 24]
    ];

    var PATTERNS = [
      { id: "straight", name: "Straight Lay", waste: 10 },
      { id: "diagonal", name: "Diagonal (45°)", waste: 15 },
      { id: "herringbone", name: "Herringbone", waste: 20 }
    ];

    var currentUnit = "ft";

    // Build tile size buttons
    var sizesEl = document.getElementById("tileSizes");
    TILE_SIZES.forEach(function(t) {
      var b = document.createElement("button");
      b.type = "button";
      b.className = "tile-btn" + (t[1] === 12 && t[2] === 12 ? " active" : "");
      b.innerHTML = '<span class="size-label">' + t[0] + '"</span><span class="size-sub">' + (t[1] * t[2]) + ' sq in</span>';
      b.addEventListener("click", function() {
        document.getElementById("tileW").value = t[1];
        document.getElementById("tileH").value = t[2];
        sizesEl.querySelectorAll(".tile-btn").forEach(function(x){ x.classList.remove("active"); });
        b.classList.add("active");
      });
      sizesEl.appendChild(b);
    });

    // Build pattern buttons
    var patEl = document.getElementById("patternOptions");
    PATTERNS.forEach(function(p) {
      var b = document.createElement("button");
      b.type = "button";
      b.className = "pattern-btn" + (p.id === "straight" ? " active" : "");
      b.innerHTML = '<span class="pat-name">' + p.name + '</span><span class="pat-waste">+' + p.waste + '% waste</span>';
      b.addEventListener("click", function() {
        document.getElementById("wasteFactor").value = p.waste;
        patEl.querySelectorAll(".pattern-btn").forEach(function(x){ x.classList.remove("active"); });
        b.classList.add("active");
      });
      patEl.appendChild(b);
    });

    // Unit toggle
    document.querySelectorAll(".unit-btn").forEach(function(btn) {
      btn.addEventListener("click", function() {
        currentUnit = this.dataset.unit;
        document.querySelectorAll(".unit-btn").forEach(function(b){ b.classList.remove("active"); });
        this.classList.add("active");
        document.getElementById("unitLabelL").textContent = currentUnit;
        document.getElementById("unitLabelW").textContent = currentUnit;
      });
    });

    function fmt(n) { return "$" + n.toFixed(2); }

    document.getElementById("calcBtn").addEventListener("click", function() {
      var roomL = parseFloat(document.getElementById("roomLength").value);
      var roomW = parseFloat(document.getElementById("roomWidth").value);
      var tileW = parseFloat(document.getElementById("tileW").value);
      var tileH = parseFloat(document.getElementById("tileH").value);
      var grout = parseFloat(document.getElementById("groutWidth").value);
      var waste = parseFloat(document.getElementById("wasteFactor").value) / 100;
      var tpb = parseInt(document.getElementById("tilesPerBox").value);
      var price = parseFloat(document.getElementById("pricePerSqft").value) || 0;

      if (isNaN(roomL) || isNaN(roomW) || isNaN(tileW) || isNaN(tileH) || roomL <= 0 || roomW <= 0) return;

      // Convert room to sq ft
      var areaSqft = roomL * roomW;
      if (currentUnit === "m") areaSqft = areaSqft * 10.7639;

      // Tile area in sq ft (tile dims in inches + grout)
      var tileTotalW = (tileW + grout) / 12;
      var tileTotalH = (tileH + grout) / 12;
      var tileAreaSqft = tileTotalW * tileTotalH;

      // Tiles needed
      var tilesRaw = areaSqft / tileAreaSqft;
      var tilesWithWaste = Math.ceil(tilesRaw * (1 + waste));
      var boxes = Math.ceil(tilesWithWaste / tpb);

      // Tile coverage (just tile face area, no grout)
      var tileFaceArea = (tileW * tileH) / 144;
      var coverageSqft = tilesWithWaste * tileFaceArea;

      // Display
      document.getElementById("rArea").textContent = areaSqft.toFixed(1);
      document.getElementById("rAreaDesc").textContent = "sq ft" + (currentUnit === "m" ? " (" + (roomL * roomW).toFixed(1) + " m\u00B2)" : "");
      document.getElementById("rTiles").textContent = tilesWithWaste;
      document.getElementById("rTilesDesc").textContent = Math.ceil(tilesRaw) + " tiles + " + Math.round(waste * 100) + "% waste";
      document.getElementById("rBoxes").textContent = boxes;
      document.getElementById("rBoxesDesc").textContent = tpb + " tiles/box";
      document.getElementById("rCoverage").textContent = coverageSqft.toFixed(1);

      // Cost
      var tileCost = coverageSqft * price;
      var groutCost = areaSqft * 0.50;
      var adhesiveCost = areaSqft * 0.75;
      var totalCost = tileCost + groutCost + adhesiveCost;

      document.getElementById("cTileArea").textContent = coverageSqft.toFixed(1) + " sq ft";
      document.getElementById("cTile").textContent = fmt(tileCost);
      document.getElementById("cGrout").textContent = fmt(groutCost);
      document.getElementById("cAdhesive").textContent = fmt(adhesiveCost);
      document.getElementById("cTotal").textContent = fmt(totalCost);
      document.getElementById("costBreakdown").style.display = price > 0 ? "block" : "none";

      document.getElementById("results").classList.add("active");
    });
  </script>

